snippet.textDisplay:
This reminds me of the book, We Need to Talk About Kevin. The book reveals a lot more of Kevin's motives than the movie does but for those of you who don't mind spoilers about the book (if you're not planning on reading it)...


**Spoiler ahead** (If you haven't seen the movie and don't want to be spoiled don't read below)


In the book, Kevin will not go to the potty properly, and throughout his young childhood, he continues to "potty" in pull-ups. He knows that this pisses his mom (Eva) off because she is the one who has to wipe him (well after age 7) and deal with his shitty diapers. One day, when Kevin is about 8 years old, he poops several times throughout the day forcing his mom to change him frequently. Eva's finally fed up and as she is about to change him, something triggers in her. She picks Kevin up and throws him against the wall. As a result, she realizes she's broken his arm. At the doctor's office, Kevin has the opportunity to tell the doctor what happened and Eva is worried because she believes that Kevin will reveal that she was the cause of the injury. However, to her absolute astonishment, Kevin lies for her and says it was his own fault that he had an accident. After this incident, Kevin and his mom keep this secret between them.


Sometime later, after Kevin is in jail, Eva asks him why he never told anyone the truth about his arm-- not even his father (Eva's husband, Franklin). Kevin explains that his dad was always trying to be his friend, and was essentially spineless and couldn't see his son for who he was (ultimately a cold-blooded killer). Kevin admits that while Eva has her flaws, throwing him against the wall was the best thing she had ever done for him.


We Need to Talk About Kevin is an absolutely chilling story about a fictional school massacre, but is filled with pieces of reality that are both shocking and raw. Although humorous, this skit reminds me of how psychotic behavior may present itself in young children -- although I don't believe the DSM recognizes psychopathy before the age of 18.
